06:34.069 --> 06:35.803
Good morning.

06:36.377 --> 06:37.310
Joel, please.

06:37.378 --> 06:38.491
Morning.
Oh, come on.

06:38.591 --> 06:40.292
I'm late.
Who's taking me to school?

06:40.360 --> 06:41.693
Your father.
Your mother.

06:41.761 --> 06:43.562
All right, two minutes--
you better be ready.

06:43.630 --> 06:44.963
And, Joel, leave your
laptop with me today, okay?

06:45.031 --> 06:46.298
My book club notes
are on it,

06:46.366 --> 06:47.716
<i>and I need to post</i>
<i>to my blog later.</i>

06:47.801 --> 06:48.734
Mom, no, okay?

06:48.802 --> 06:50.302
It's my laptop now.

06:50.370 --> 06:52.304
And don't use
the word "blog."

06:52.372 --> 06:54.139
It embarrasses me
for you.

06:54.207 --> 06:56.475
You and me both.
<i>Richard!</i>

06:56.543 --> 06:58.444
Well, you know, you shouldn't
be gossiping like that.

06:58.511 --> 07:00.212
What are they
arguing about?

07:00.280 --> 07:02.481
Something about a blog?

07:02.549 --> 07:04.316
Oh, brother.

07:04.384 --> 07:06.418
Of course it's gossip.

07:06.486 --> 07:07.986
Excuse me, folks.
I'm sorry to interrupt--

07:08.054 --> 07:09.321
Honey,
that's ridiculous.

07:09.389 --> 07:11.022
It's an art form, not--

07:11.074 --> 07:12.925
That's not gonna happen.

07:16.663 --> 07:18.330
I'm sorry,

07:18.398 --> 07:20.532
but there are a few things
we need to discuss here.

07:20.600 --> 07:23.569
Wow. You're
an excellent whistler.

07:23.636 --> 07:25.737
Thank you.

07:25.805 --> 07:27.272
So here's the procedure.

07:27.340 --> 07:29.608
We're gonna be protecting
each one of you individually.

07:29.676 --> 07:31.910
<i>Richard, Chance is gonna go</i>
<i>with you to work.</i>

07:31.978 --> 07:34.446
I'm gonna be the new
Hoxton-Moss office temp.

07:34.514 --> 07:37.249
Office temp...

07:37.317 --> 07:39.084
That sounds exciting.

07:39.152 --> 07:41.286
Who is she?
<i>This is Ames.</i>

07:41.354 --> 07:42.855
<i>Joel, Ames is going</i>
<i>to school with you</i>

07:42.922 --> 07:45.390
and then to your job
after school at the mall

07:45.458 --> 07:47.059
<i>and then back here</i>
<i>this evening.</i>

07:47.127 --> 07:48.694
Hey, Joel.
Don't worry.

07:48.761 --> 07:52.080
I'll try not to cramp
your style too much.

07:53.766 --> 07:55.100
Close your mouth, son.

07:55.168 --> 07:57.402
Rachel, I'm gonna be here
with you.

07:57.470 --> 07:59.505
Here? But I'm having
my book club over today.

07:59.572 --> 08:01.140
We're starting
<i>The Secret Life of Bees.</i>

08:01.207 --> 08:03.742
No problem.
I'm familiar with it.

08:03.810 --> 08:06.879
And who is that
near my roses?

08:06.946 --> 08:09.114
<i>Oh, that's Guerrero.</i>

08:09.182 --> 08:11.083
He's just checking
for bugs.

08:11.151 --> 08:12.317
Bugs?

08:12.385 --> 08:14.286
Not bugs...

08:14.354 --> 08:17.089
<i>Like your...</i>

08:17.157 --> 08:19.291
Forget--
do you have any more bagels?

08:19.359 --> 08:21.793
Of course.
Anybody else?

08:21.861 --> 08:23.295
<i>Yes, please.</i>

08:28.952 --> 08:31.436
Hoxton-Moss--
how may I help you?

08:31.504 --> 08:33.739
Hoxton-Moss Pharmaceuticals.

08:33.789 --> 08:36.107
<i>Hoxton-Moss Pharmaceuticals.</i>

08:36.176 --> 08:37.943
Ah, there he is--

08:37.994 --> 08:39.578
<i>my boss,</i>
<i>Nick Meachem.</i>

08:39.645 --> 08:40.779
<i>So he's the one</i>

08:40.847 --> 08:42.464
you think is behind
the attack, huh?

08:42.549 --> 08:44.149
Yeah, well, before I wrote
the letter, I went to him,

08:44.217 --> 08:46.485
and, uh, he said there's
problems with the research.

08:46.553 --> 08:48.136
He said those were
the sorts of objections

08:48.221 --> 08:50.255
that could get an employee
into serious trouble,

08:50.306 --> 08:51.924
and he said it
with real menace.

08:51.991 --> 08:53.692
He's one of the people
I named in the letter.

08:53.760 --> 08:55.127
A janitor?

08:55.195 --> 08:57.262
Your cover is office temp?

08:57.330 --> 08:58.664
I'm a janitor?

08:58.731 --> 09:00.849
You got something
against an honest day's work?

09:00.934 --> 09:03.602
Uh, yeah,
actually, I do.

09:03.670 --> 09:05.187
Applebaum.

09:06.339 --> 09:08.140
You're late.

09:08.208 --> 09:10.108
Good morning, sir.

09:10.176 --> 09:12.110
Morning.
Who are you?

09:12.161 --> 09:14.646
Collingsworth--
Paul Collingsworth.

09:14.714 --> 09:17.816
Little help here,
Applebaum.

09:17.884 --> 09:19.284
I am the new
office temp.

09:19.352 --> 09:21.687
My agency worked it out
with H.R.

09:21.754 --> 09:23.488
<i>Today's my first day</i>
<i>with Hoxton-Moss.</i>

09:23.556 --> 09:25.457
<i>I've been temping</i>
<i>for ages.</i>

09:25.525 --> 09:29.027
Temp work is anything but
temporary for me, you might say.

09:29.095 --> 09:30.929
You might say,
not me.

09:30.997 --> 09:32.164
Richard...

09:32.232 --> 09:34.866
I need your assessment reports
A.S.A.P., okay?

09:34.934 --> 09:36.051
Then come and find me.

09:36.135 --> 09:37.853
There are some things
we need to discuss...

09:37.937 --> 09:39.054
Privately.

09:39.138 --> 09:41.039
<i>Hoxton-Moss Pharmaceuticals.</i>

09:41.107 --> 09:42.140
<i>Please hold.</i>

09:42.191 --> 09:43.976
What the--
sorry, sir.

09:45.645 --> 09:48.680
<i>I'll transfer you to...</i>

09:48.748 --> 09:51.083
I put a tracker on him
when we shook hands.

09:51.150 --> 09:52.985
Just lifted his keys.

09:53.036 --> 09:54.987
I kind of like to think
a placed tracker

09:55.054 --> 09:56.572
beats lifted keys,
don't you?

09:56.656 --> 09:58.189
No, I don't.

09:58.241 --> 10:00.459
And while we're, uh,
sharing our opinions...

10:03.096 --> 10:04.663
Dude!

10:04.731 --> 10:06.898
<i>What, you...</i>

10:06.966 --> 10:08.400
Raised in a barn
or something?

10:08.468 --> 10:09.468
Pick it up.

10:20.930 --> 10:25.734
♪ ♪

10:25.818 --> 10:27.069
This place sucks.

10:27.153 --> 10:30.272
I mean, all the action's
on the other side of the mall.

10:30.356 --> 10:33.225
Seriously, though, I feel like
I owe you an apology.

10:33.293 --> 10:36.395
I mean, it's one thing
for me to live my crappy life,

10:36.462 --> 10:40.065
but making you do it, too,
is just cruel and unusual.

10:40.133 --> 10:43.101
Are you kidding?
Free hot dogs...

10:43.169 --> 10:46.071
If this ain't living,
I don't know what is.

10:46.139 --> 10:47.406
<i>Excuse me,</i>
<i>can I get a--</i>

10:47.473 --> 10:48.974
hey, Joel.

10:49.042 --> 10:50.575
Jamie.

10:50.643 --> 10:52.377
Hi. Hi, um...
<i>Hi.</i>

10:52.445 --> 10:54.546
I mean,
do you want something?

10:54.597 --> 10:57.716
I-I mean--I mean,
w-what would you like?

10:57.767 --> 10:59.584
I-I mean, w-what can I do
for you that you--

10:59.652 --> 11:00.986
that you would like?

11:01.054 --> 11:03.388
Just a hot dog...
With mustard.

11:03.456 --> 11:06.858
Mustard--yeah, we have, uh,
great-quality mustard here.

11:06.926 --> 11:09.728
We, uh--we specially make it
with our special ingredients,

11:09.796 --> 11:13.131
you know, to really, you know,
bring out the flavors.

11:13.199 --> 11:15.400
So it's not so, like,
mustard-y, you know?

11:15.451 --> 11:16.635
You're funny, Joel.

11:16.703 --> 11:20.038
Extra mustard,
on the house.

11:20.106 --> 11:21.540
Thanks.

11:21.607 --> 11:24.543
So are you going
to Billy Backer's party tonight?

11:27.013 --> 11:29.181
Uh, probably not.

11:29.248 --> 11:31.550
I mean, my parents have,
you know, um...

11:31.617 --> 11:32.751
Sort of got me

11:32.819 --> 11:34.386
<i>on a tight leash,</i>
<i>you know,</i>

11:34.454 --> 11:36.955
almost, uh, noose-like.

11:37.006 --> 11:39.057
Bummer.

11:39.125 --> 11:41.326
Well, only because
you always...

11:41.394 --> 11:43.261
Play such cool music,

11:43.329 --> 11:44.930
and Billy's stuff
is always so lousy.

11:44.997 --> 11:48.400
Well, uh,
I'll see you tomorrow.

11:48.467 --> 11:51.036
See ya.
<i>Let me guess--</i>
<i>you like her.</i>

11:51.104 --> 11:53.405
I mean, obviously
she's not interested.

11:55.108 --> 11:57.442
Come on, Joel, wake up
and smell the mustard.

11:57.493 --> 12:00.545
She just invited you
to a party.

12:00.613 --> 12:02.614
You think?

12:02.682 --> 12:04.216
Yeah.

12:07.019 --> 12:10.288
Any chance you think
my parents might let me go?

12:12.191 --> 12:15.677
Not until we find out
who's trying to kill 'em.

12:25.171 --> 12:29.975
♪ ♪

12:42.422 --> 12:44.740
I'm literally...

12:44.824 --> 12:46.725
In hell.

12:49.829 --> 12:54.332
Hoxton-Moss--
Paul Collingsworth speaking.

12:54.400 --> 12:55.533
Hey, Meachem just said

12:55.585 --> 12:57.369
that the company
knows about the letter.

12:57.437 --> 12:58.904
Did he accuse you
of writing it?

12:58.971 --> 13:00.872
Uh, well, no,
not directly,

13:00.940 --> 13:02.874
but he told me to go downstairs
to the archives

13:02.942 --> 13:04.075
to get a file.

13:04.143 --> 13:06.344
<i>There's nothing down there</i>

13:06.412 --> 13:07.879
that can't be accessed
by this computer.

13:07.947 --> 13:09.881
I'm telling you, Chance,
the archives are empty.

13:09.949 --> 13:11.583
He's up to something.
It's a setup!

13:11.651 --> 13:12.884
That's good.

13:12.952 --> 13:14.886
What--it's what?
It's not good.

13:14.937 --> 13:16.555
It's bad.
It's the opposite of good.

13:16.622 --> 13:17.722
It is a good thing.

13:17.790 --> 13:19.791
It just means this is
gonna come to an end quicker

13:19.859 --> 13:21.893
for both of us.

13:21.961 --> 13:24.863
Richard, you have
to trust me, okay?

13:27.633 --> 13:29.618
All right.

13:39.712 --> 13:40.629
Yo.

13:40.713 --> 13:41.880
Where are you?

13:41.948 --> 13:43.281
Restocking.
Why? What's up?

13:43.349 --> 13:44.716
Well, now would be
a good time

13:44.784 --> 13:47.752
for the janitor to check
the trash in Meachem's office.

13:47.820 --> 13:49.688
Got it.
On my way.

14:26.158 --> 14:27.826
<i>We got him.</i>

14:27.894 --> 14:31.096
Go, now.

15:03.996 --> 15:05.564
Hello, Richard.
Oh!

15:05.631 --> 15:08.033
We know it was you
who wrote the FDA.

15:08.100 --> 15:10.368
Okay, Nick,
don't come any closer.

15:10.436 --> 15:12.370
What were you thinking?

15:12.438 --> 15:14.306
Do you have any idea
what you have done?

15:14.373 --> 15:17.642
You made a huge mistake,
Richard,

15:17.710 --> 15:19.477
don't do that.
You'll re--Nick!

15:21.247 --> 15:23.014
What the...?

15:23.082 --> 15:25.550
You selfish son of a bitch!

15:25.618 --> 15:26.902
How could you do this
to the company?

15:26.986 --> 15:29.354
Who the hell are you again?
Collingsworth.

15:29.422 --> 15:30.822
Paul Collingsworth, the temp.
The temp?

15:30.890 --> 15:32.657
<i>When I saw him</i>
<i>about to attack you, well...</i>

15:32.725 --> 15:35.193
I knew I had to do something.

15:35.244 --> 15:37.562
Ow!

15:39.832 --> 15:42.000
This is a list
of all the people

15:42.068 --> 15:43.668
<i>who could lose their jobs</i>
<i>because of your letter.</i>

15:43.719 --> 15:45.870
Nick!
Can I call you Nick?

15:45.938 --> 15:47.105
<i>Is it okay with you</i>

15:47.173 --> 15:49.374
if I escort this lowlife
right out of the building?

15:49.442 --> 15:51.376
Come on, you.

15:51.444 --> 15:52.844
This isn't over, Richard.

15:52.912 --> 15:54.846
You will be hearing
from our attorneys.

15:54.914 --> 15:56.481
Yeah.

15:58.351 --> 15:59.451
All right.

15:59.518 --> 16:02.153
I guess Meachem's
not trying to kill me.

16:02.221 --> 16:04.656
The question is now,
who is?

16:08.427 --> 16:10.195
Mm, mm, mm!

16:10.262 --> 16:11.363
Winston, help!

16:11.430 --> 16:12.797
What--
did you see something?

16:12.865 --> 16:15.800
No, it's
this damn laptop.

16:15.868 --> 16:18.370
I can't seem to find
my book club notes anywhere.

16:18.437 --> 16:20.538
Joel must have
put them somewhere.

16:20.606 --> 16:21.873
Mm.

16:21.941 --> 16:23.708
All right, let me
take a crack at it.

16:23.776 --> 16:25.243
Ah, thank you.

16:25.311 --> 16:27.078
I'm just not myself
these days.

16:27.146 --> 16:28.246
None of us are.

16:28.314 --> 16:29.614
I'm sure you've noticed

16:29.682 --> 16:31.616
how short Richard and I
have been with each other.

16:31.684 --> 16:33.134
Well, I've been married
before.

16:33.219 --> 16:35.487
It kind of comes
with the territory.

16:35.554 --> 16:37.772
The other night, he was so
on edge that he snapped at me

16:37.857 --> 16:39.991
for wanting to put up
the Christmas decorations.

16:40.059 --> 16:41.943
He did?

16:42.028 --> 16:44.829
Do you know that Chance
doesn't even want us to have

16:44.897 --> 16:46.648
a Christmas tree
in the office?

16:46.732 --> 16:48.400
You believe that?

16:48.467 --> 16:49.901
Oh, no.
Is it really necessary

16:49.969 --> 16:52.904
for your people to ruin
all of my landscaping?

16:52.972 --> 16:53.972
What are you talk--

16:55.307 --> 16:56.474
Get down.
Aah!

17:01.547 --> 17:02.747
Get back
in the laundry room.

17:02.815 --> 17:04.315
Keep the door closed
and stay down!

17:07.920 --> 17:09.054
Aah!

17:16.028 --> 17:18.396
Aah!

17:44.890 --> 17:48.193
Is, uh,
book club canceled?

17:49.295 --> 17:50.829
Uh...

17:50.896 --> 17:52.163
Rachel.

17:56.827 --> 17:58.845
One of the guys who attacked
the house this afternoon

17:58.912 --> 17:59.746
dropped his cell phone.

17:59.749 --> 18:00.883
Guerrero's busy
trying to pull

18:00.951 --> 18:02.418
whatever information
he can out of there.

18:02.485 --> 18:03.719
Rachel, could you think
of a reason

18:03.787 --> 18:05.187
why someone
would want to kill you?

18:05.255 --> 18:06.689
Me? No!

18:06.756 --> 18:08.858
Oh, my God.
<i>Of course not--</i>

18:08.925 --> 18:11.026
it's her blog!
What?

18:11.094 --> 18:12.595
Her blog.
She has a blog.

18:12.662 --> 18:14.263
It's about the whole town,
and it's filled with gossip.

18:14.331 --> 18:15.431
<i>What are you</i>
<i>talking about?</i>

18:15.498 --> 18:17.867
What I post
is totally innocuous.

18:17.934 --> 18:19.568
You wrote about Ron Moodie.
He had an affair.

18:19.636 --> 18:20.603
That's what you wrote.

18:20.670 --> 18:21.837
<i>Then his wife left him.</i>

18:21.905 --> 18:23.405
<i>And then Amy O'Connell--</i>

18:23.473 --> 18:25.174
she writes that she's cheating
on her taxes.

18:25.242 --> 18:27.276
You can't get into people's
business like that, honey.

18:27.344 --> 18:28.944
They come and get you!
It's one of my creative...

18:29.012 --> 18:30.546
This is ridiculous.

18:30.614 --> 18:33.315
Blog? What do you say
we just tie them up

18:33.383 --> 18:35.284
and let Guerrero
handle the rest of it?

18:35.352 --> 18:37.553
You serious? There's some
duct tape right there.

18:39.122 --> 18:40.289
You don't understand.

18:40.357 --> 18:42.258
You know, you don't appreciate
what I do--

18:46.029 --> 18:47.463
I've been shot at.

18:47.530 --> 18:49.398
I've been thrown
out of an airplane,

18:49.466 --> 18:52.001
been generally mistreated
by a lot of very bad people.

18:52.068 --> 18:54.103
But this bickering is pretty
much more than I can take,

18:54.170 --> 18:55.971
so I'm gonna go outside
and get some fresh air.

18:56.039 --> 18:58.841
When I get back, you two
had better be calmed down,

18:58.909 --> 19:00.476
or we're breaking out
the ball gags.

19:00.543 --> 19:03.145
Wow.

19:03.213 --> 19:05.648
He's a good whistler too.

19:05.715 --> 19:08.417
What's going on
down there?

19:08.485 --> 19:10.185
Chance and Winston
are, uh...

19:10.253 --> 19:11.954
Helping your parents
communicate a little better.

19:12.022 --> 19:13.555
<i>It's nothing</i>
<i>to worry about, okay?</i>

19:13.623 --> 19:15.691
I can practically see
Billy Backer's house from here.

19:15.759 --> 19:17.993
Oh, right, yeah,
the party that Jamie mentioned.

19:18.061 --> 19:19.795
The one that she
invited me to.

19:19.863 --> 19:23.332
That was pretty cool.

19:23.400 --> 19:26.335
Yeah, it was.
It was pretty cool.

19:26.403 --> 19:27.536
Do you want to go?

19:27.604 --> 19:28.837
Where?

19:28.905 --> 19:30.906
The party.

19:30.974 --> 19:32.908
We'll just go out the window,
climb down the trellis.

19:32.976 --> 19:34.443
No one's gonna even know
we're gone.

19:34.511 --> 19:36.078
Seriously?

19:36.146 --> 19:37.579
You mean, like,
sneak out?

19:37.647 --> 19:39.648
I've never actually
done that before.

19:39.716 --> 19:42.518
Then, jeez, it's time
to pop your cherry--

19:42.585 --> 19:45.587
I mean, as far as
sneaking out goes.

19:45.655 --> 19:47.389
That's where the proverbial
cherry popping stops.

19:47.457 --> 19:50.092
But if we leave, that means
that Chance and Winston

19:50.160 --> 19:52.127
are gonna have to protect
mom and dad by themselves.

19:52.195 --> 19:54.430
Yes, that's a very good point
you make there, Joel,

19:54.497 --> 19:56.265
and while I do appreciate
that you realize

19:56.333 --> 19:58.300
that I am the muscle
behind this operation,

19:58.351 --> 19:59.935
uh, in this instance,

20:00.003 --> 20:01.704
I think your mom and dad
are gonna be good.

20:01.771 --> 20:03.005
I don't know.

20:03.073 --> 20:04.690
Oh, come on,
take it from me,

20:04.774 --> 20:08.243
sometimes being bad
can feel pretty good.

20:10.347 --> 20:12.114
Okay.

20:14.985 --> 20:18.220
Oh, uh, you might want
to leave the laptop here.

20:18.288 --> 20:20.622
But all my music is on it,

20:20.690 --> 20:24.793
and Jamie said that she
likes my music, remember?

20:24.861 --> 20:26.962
Okay.

20:32.669 --> 20:33.869
Just don't embarrass me,
okay, Ames?

20:33.937 --> 20:35.337
And no telling anyone
that you're my bodyguard.

20:35.405 --> 20:36.805
Okay. Got it.

20:36.873 --> 20:38.374
Hey.
Hold it there, buddy.

20:38.441 --> 20:40.909
Jonas Brothers fan club
meets down the street.

20:40.977 --> 20:43.145
Hold it there, Joel.

20:43.213 --> 20:45.114
You're with him?

20:45.181 --> 20:47.249
Yeah. You got a problem
with that?

20:51.521 --> 20:54.790
So what do you think?
It's fun, right?

20:54.858 --> 20:57.259
Yeah. I can't believe
I'm actually here.

20:57.327 --> 20:58.260
Thanks, Ames.

20:58.328 --> 20:59.962
No worries.

21:00.030 --> 21:01.630
Joel!

21:01.698 --> 21:02.948
Cool! You came.

21:03.033 --> 21:04.700
Jamie, hi.
<i>Cool!</i>

21:06.169 --> 21:08.404
Oh, I-I'm gonna go
and grab a beer.

21:08.471 --> 21:09.705
<i>Um, I'll be right back.</i>

21:11.374 --> 21:12.775
Is that
your girlfriend?

21:12.842 --> 21:16.011
Well, um...
We used to date,

21:16.079 --> 21:18.247
but now we're,
you know, just friends.

21:18.314 --> 21:20.215
Okay.

21:30.126 --> 21:33.462
Putting aside the blog
hypothesis for a minute,

21:33.530 --> 21:35.798
earlier this afternoon,
Guerrero found a business card

21:35.865 --> 21:38.100
in Meachem's office with
a Swedish address and number.

21:38.168 --> 21:39.635
Does that mean
anything to you?

21:39.702 --> 21:40.736
Swedish?

21:40.804 --> 21:43.272
Uh, well, look...

21:43.339 --> 21:44.873
The guys who ran us
off the road that night,

21:44.941 --> 21:46.308
they were not speaking
english.

21:46.376 --> 21:48.143
I couldn't place it at the time.
It could have been Swedish.

21:48.211 --> 21:49.645
Aren't the Klaxons
from the down the street

21:49.712 --> 21:51.080
originally from Sweden?

21:51.147 --> 21:53.132
No, no. They're just Canadian.
Oh, that's right.

21:54.751 --> 21:56.251
Yeah, what do you got?

21:56.319 --> 21:57.786
Guerrero.

21:57.837 --> 21:59.488
Yeah, the thugs
that showed up at book club

21:59.556 --> 22:01.473
work for a guy by the name
of Severenson Klemah.

22:01.558 --> 22:03.325
He's a Swedish
game-designer-turned-hacker.

22:03.393 --> 22:06.195
He now specializes in something
called "zombie-bots."

22:06.262 --> 22:08.847
Zombie what?
<i>It's invisible software</i>

22:08.932 --> 22:10.182
buried deep inside
a computer game.

22:10.266 --> 22:12.101
When you play the game, software
takes over your computer

22:12.152 --> 22:13.268
without you realizing it,

22:13.336 --> 22:14.803
kind of making your computer,
you know...

22:14.871 --> 22:16.305
Oh, zombie--
right, clever.

22:16.372 --> 22:17.406
<i>Yeah.</i>

22:17.474 --> 22:19.274
So this guy pays off Meachem

22:19.342 --> 22:21.410
for emails
to Hoxton-Moss employees.

22:21.478 --> 22:22.978
They play the game--bam.

22:23.029 --> 22:25.314
They've got access
to the company server.

22:25.381 --> 22:26.882
<i>That's pretty damn clever.</i>

22:26.950 --> 22:29.051
Yeah. Wish I'd have thought
of it myself.

22:29.119 --> 22:31.453
So anyone in the family
a gamer?

22:45.368 --> 22:47.553
Okay, look,
before you start on me--

22:47.637 --> 22:49.204
where the hell are you?
You have Joel?

22:49.272 --> 22:51.723
Yes, and
everything's fine.

22:51.808 --> 22:53.475
<i>We're just at a house party</i>
<i>down the street--</i>

22:53.543 --> 22:55.210
<i>Ames, Joel is the one</i>
<i>they're after.</i>

22:55.278 --> 22:57.346
<i>Not the father,</i>
<i>not the mother--it's Joel.</i>

22:57.413 --> 22:59.882
Right. Well, uh, that explains
the two professional

22:59.949 --> 23:01.583
mouth breathers
that just walked in.

23:01.651 --> 23:03.085
Look, we're down the street.
Just get here now.

23:03.153 --> 23:04.419
Stay here!

23:04.487 --> 23:07.022
I have Vargas for science
too-- we gotta talk.

23:07.090 --> 23:08.690
<i>Joel?</i>
What are you doing?

23:08.758 --> 23:10.492
We totally were connecting.
Oh, that's awesome, Joel.

23:10.560 --> 23:12.594
Less awesome is the fact
that two thugs just walked in

23:12.662 --> 23:15.063
apparently looking for you.
What?

23:15.131 --> 23:16.899
Friends of yours?

23:21.037 --> 23:22.504
What?
Get out of the way, man!

23:22.572 --> 23:23.839
Hey!

23:30.079 --> 23:32.214
<i>Whoa!</i>

23:32.265 --> 23:34.716
<i>Joel Applebaum's</i>
<i>getting his ass kicked!</i>

23:36.853 --> 23:39.755
<i>Run, Joel, run.</i>

23:41.057 --> 23:44.059
Aah!

23:46.296 --> 23:48.197
<i>Ooh! That's gonna</i>
<i>leave a mark.</i>

23:51.634 --> 23:53.368
Ames, you okay?

24:03.313 --> 24:05.781
<i>Oh, holy Christmas!</i>

24:05.848 --> 24:07.382
Gnarly.

24:07.433 --> 24:10.385
Is that dude
with Joel Applebaum?

24:10.453 --> 24:12.154
Yeah, he is.

24:12.222 --> 24:15.440
Stay off drugs.
I'll be watching.

24:26.888 --> 24:28.622
You call this protection?

24:28.690 --> 24:31.658
In the course of one day,
one single day,

24:31.726 --> 24:33.327
Chance levels me
like a linebacker,

24:33.394 --> 24:36.129
my wife is shot at
and shoved into a closet,

24:36.180 --> 24:37.597
and my son is nearly killed
at a kegger!

24:37.649 --> 24:39.132
We understand
this might seem

24:39.183 --> 24:41.184
a little unorthodox
to you, Mr. Applebaum.

24:41.269 --> 24:42.536
<i>Joel...</i>

24:42.603 --> 24:45.505
You ever play a game
called <i>Zombie Circus?</i>

24:45.573 --> 24:47.841
Um, yeah.

24:47.909 --> 24:50.377
I got an email
offering me

24:50.445 --> 24:53.146
a free 30-day trial
of the game,

24:53.214 --> 24:55.215
and I played it.

24:55.283 --> 24:58.285
And, well, the game
totally sucked.

24:58.353 --> 25:00.821
Even worse, it practically
shredded my hard drive

25:00.888 --> 25:02.622
with some sort of virus.

25:02.690 --> 25:04.324
<i>I-I got angry.</i>

25:04.392 --> 25:08.295
I hacked into the site of
the company that made the game.

25:08.363 --> 25:09.863
I wanted to teach them
a lesson,

25:09.931 --> 25:11.398
so I erased
all their files.

25:11.466 --> 25:12.866
You--what did you do?
Joel!

25:12.934 --> 25:14.234
I know.
I'm sorry.

25:14.302 --> 25:16.053
<i>Okay?</i>
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

25:16.137 --> 25:18.572
I was just so angry,
and I didn't think that--

25:18.639 --> 25:20.574
that, you know, something
like this would happen.

25:20.641 --> 25:23.243
<i>It seems your little</i>
<i>hacking job effectively erased</i>

25:23.311 --> 25:25.912
all of Klemah's
stolen Hoxton-Moss files,

25:25.980 --> 25:28.448
<i>which we can assume</i>
<i>were very valuable.</i>

25:28.516 --> 25:29.983
But there are still
some copies

25:30.051 --> 25:31.818
of the stolen files
on your laptop.

25:31.869 --> 25:33.870
S-so what--now these guys
want to kill me?

25:40.728 --> 25:43.263
<i>Why are your feet</i>
<i>on my desk?</i>

25:43.331 --> 25:44.898
Who are you?

25:44.966 --> 25:47.734
The janitor.
Have a seat.

25:47.802 --> 25:49.403
Get out of my office.

25:56.077 --> 25:57.978
You, Nick...

25:58.045 --> 25:59.346
<i>Are what we</i>

25:59.414 --> 26:03.016
in the custodial arts
like to call a real douche.

26:03.084 --> 26:05.585
<i>Tell me how I can get in touch</i>
<i>with Severenson Klemah,</i>

26:05.653 --> 26:07.287
who we both know
you're in business with.

26:07.355 --> 26:09.890
<i>My boss wants to talk</i>
<i>to your boss.</i>

26:09.957 --> 26:11.891
You're gonna help.

26:11.943 --> 26:13.794
And I really hate having
to explain myself

26:13.861 --> 26:15.529
to people
in your position, so...

26:15.596 --> 26:18.932
Let's just say,
in this case, uh...

26:19.000 --> 26:21.034
It's gonna involve
this stapler.

26:21.102 --> 26:23.036
I'm calling security.

26:23.104 --> 26:25.005
Aah! Aah! Aah!

26:26.240 --> 26:28.942
<i>Now, how do I contact</i>
<i>Klemah?</i>

26:29.010 --> 26:30.410
<i>Aah!</i>

26:30.478 --> 26:32.379
Crappy office, by the way.

26:36.150 --> 26:37.551
Yes.

26:37.618 --> 26:38.718
<i>We have the laptop.</i>

26:38.770 --> 26:40.253
And who would I be
speaking with?

26:40.321 --> 26:41.855
Oh, that's irrelevant.
What's important

26:41.923 --> 26:43.723
is we're willing to arrange
to give it back to you

26:43.791 --> 26:45.992
in exchange for you leaving
Joel and his family alone.

26:46.060 --> 26:48.562
<i>So where and when would you</i>
<i>like to conduct the exchange?</i>

26:48.613 --> 26:51.615
Well, let's see.
How about...

26:51.699 --> 26:54.701
This afternoon in the mall

26:54.769 --> 26:57.804
where young Joel
sells hot dogs?

26:57.872 --> 27:01.408
<i>A nice public place,</i>
<i>lots of innocent bystanders.</i>

27:01.476 --> 27:03.410
<i>I will send a man,</i>

27:03.478 --> 27:05.512
<i>and you send Joel</i>
<i>with the laptop.</i>

27:05.580 --> 27:06.630
Joel?

27:06.714 --> 27:09.950
<i>Yes.</i>
<i>And if we see</i>

27:10.017 --> 27:11.618
anyone else but him--

27:11.669 --> 27:15.021
you, the police, anyone--

27:15.089 --> 27:16.857
then the whole family dies.

27:16.924 --> 27:20.260
<i>Maybe not right away, hmm?</i>
<i>But eventually.</i>

27:20.328 --> 27:21.761
<i>You can't protect them</i>
<i>forever,</i>

27:21.829 --> 27:25.098
whoever you are.

27:25.166 --> 27:26.867
Do we have a deal?

27:30.972 --> 27:33.373
Yeah.
You got a deal.

27:33.441 --> 27:35.142
Absolutely not.

27:35.209 --> 27:36.443
It's not gonna happen.

27:36.511 --> 27:38.028
At least they agree
on something.

27:38.112 --> 27:39.746
Richard, Rachel,
listen, just hear us out.

27:39.814 --> 27:42.048
We understand your concerns,
but we can protect Joel.

27:42.116 --> 27:43.917
Not sending him means
this thing just continues.

27:43.985 --> 27:45.818
Now, Klemah was right
about one thing.

27:45.870 --> 27:47.154
We can't protect you
forever.

27:47.221 --> 27:48.555
Mr. Chance,

27:48.623 --> 27:51.525
you must realize that Joel's
not like one of you.

27:51.592 --> 27:53.527
He's...

27:53.594 --> 27:55.729
Well, he's practically
afraid of his own shadow.

27:59.567 --> 28:01.635
You mind if I talk
to Joel alone?

28:04.805 --> 28:07.140
All right.

28:09.410 --> 28:11.478
Make sure he don't hack
into anything.

28:12.680 --> 28:14.014
<i>Joel...</i>

28:14.081 --> 28:16.349
Why don't you give the computer
a rest, have a seat?

28:16.417 --> 28:18.718
Is everything okay?
Yeah.

28:25.126 --> 28:27.027
So how you holding up?

28:27.094 --> 28:29.412
Okay, I guess.

28:29.497 --> 28:31.831
I mean, I still can't believe
all this is all my fault.

28:31.899 --> 28:34.234
No, it's not your fault.

28:34.302 --> 28:36.169
But here's the situation.

28:36.237 --> 28:38.138
I spoke with the guy
who wants the computer.

28:38.206 --> 28:40.240
He said he's willing
to call off the dogs

28:40.308 --> 28:42.142
if we give it back to him,
but the condition is

28:42.209 --> 28:44.311
you've got to bring it
to him this afternoon personally

28:44.378 --> 28:47.247
at the mall where you work.
Me?

28:49.450 --> 28:52.385
Jeez, this really is shaping up
to be the worst Christmas ever.

28:52.453 --> 28:54.387
Yeah, well, they're all
equally annoying, if you ask me.

28:54.455 --> 28:56.022
But then again,
I didn't grow up

28:56.073 --> 28:57.724
with the kind
of family you have.

28:57.792 --> 28:59.859
Your parents care about you
a great deal.

28:59.911 --> 29:01.695
So you can imagine
they're not too thrilled

29:01.762 --> 29:04.731
about the idea
of you making the exchange.

29:04.799 --> 29:06.766
But you think I should.

29:06.834 --> 29:09.603
I know we can protect you.

29:09.670 --> 29:13.306
What matters is whether or not
you think you can do it.

29:13.374 --> 29:16.776
If you can't,
don't worry about it.

29:16.844 --> 29:18.878
We'll find another way.

29:24.785 --> 29:27.554
But if you ask me,
in this life,

29:27.622 --> 29:29.055
you get pushed around

29:29.123 --> 29:33.326
just about as long
as you don't push back.

29:35.112 --> 29:36.763
For what it's worth,
if he says he can do this,

29:36.831 --> 29:38.565
I think we can pull it off.

29:38.633 --> 29:41.067
Okay, you're saying this whole
thing rests on Joel's decision.

29:41.135 --> 29:42.319
That is patently absurd.

29:42.403 --> 29:43.570
He is not old enough

29:43.621 --> 29:45.305
to decide something like this
for himself.

29:45.373 --> 29:46.606
He's 16 years old.

29:46.674 --> 29:48.742
I think you're wrong.

29:48.809 --> 29:52.078
Dad, I can do it.

29:52.146 --> 29:54.314
I really think that
I can do it--we can do it.

29:54.382 --> 29:56.816
Yeah, well, it's not open
for discussion, Joel.

29:56.884 --> 29:57.951
<i>Have a seat.</i>

29:58.019 --> 29:59.786
Chance, Winston,
and Ames can protect me.

29:59.854 --> 30:01.988
I trust them to,
and--and you should too.

30:02.056 --> 30:05.258
I mean, what's
the alternative, run forever?

30:05.326 --> 30:06.459
Kid has a point.

30:08.796 --> 30:10.630
Mr. Chance...

30:10.698 --> 30:12.632
Do you have children?

30:12.700 --> 30:13.633
No.

30:13.701 --> 30:16.269
Close family?
No.

30:16.337 --> 30:18.204
All due respect,

30:18.272 --> 30:21.308
I don't think you understand
what you're asking of us.

30:21.375 --> 30:23.343
You know,
maybe you're right.

30:23.411 --> 30:25.779
Maybe I don't have any idea
what it's like to have a family,

30:25.846 --> 30:27.647
but I do know
how to protect one,

30:27.715 --> 30:29.683
better than anyone.

30:29.750 --> 30:31.484
<i>Now, you let Joel do this,</i>
<i>we put these guys away,</i>

30:31.552 --> 30:33.687
and you and your family
get your lives back.

30:33.754 --> 30:35.388
But that is not something

30:35.456 --> 30:38.291
that you can
absolutely promise, is it?

30:38.359 --> 30:41.461
I just did.

30:55.537 --> 30:57.088
All right, Joel
you got any questions?

30:57.178 --> 30:58.612
You feel good
about everything?

30:58.644 --> 31:00.011
I think I'm fine.

31:00.034 --> 31:01.935
Klemah emailed me a picture of
the guy you're gonna be meeting.

31:02.002 --> 31:03.336
He's gonna be sitting
at a table

31:03.387 --> 31:05.171
right in front
of the hot dog stand.

31:05.239 --> 31:07.006
<i>And all Joel is gonna do</i>

31:07.057 --> 31:08.341
is put this laptop
on a table

31:08.392 --> 31:10.376
- and just walk away, right?
- Exactly.

31:10.444 --> 31:12.011
It's okay.
Chance, Winston, and Guerrero

31:12.079 --> 31:13.847
are gonna there be with him
the whole way, okay?

31:13.914 --> 31:15.782
He's gonna have a mic
and a camera on him.

31:15.849 --> 31:17.717
We're gonna be able to hear
and see everything.

31:17.785 --> 31:19.552
<i>Now, Joel, once</i>
<i>you've made the drop</i>

31:19.620 --> 31:20.653
and you're back here safely,

31:20.721 --> 31:22.288
we're gonna follow
the laptop to Klemah.

31:22.356 --> 31:24.290
We'll take him out, by which
time you're gonna be back here

31:24.358 --> 31:26.759
with your dad and Ames.
Okay.

31:26.827 --> 31:28.795
<i>All right? Now I'm gonna</i>
<i>go get into position.</i>

31:28.863 --> 31:30.363
Ames is gonna tell you
when to move. Hey...

31:30.431 --> 31:31.498
You're gonna be great.

31:40.808 --> 31:44.244
Chance...

31:44.311 --> 31:48.214
Uh, I want you
to understand...

31:48.282 --> 31:51.151
He's my son.

31:53.621 --> 31:55.822
He's all we got.

31:55.890 --> 31:59.092
Richard, I'm not gonna let
anything happen to him.

32:15.910 --> 32:18.778
Are you okay,
Mr. Applebaum?

32:18.846 --> 32:20.747
I'm doing my best.

32:20.814 --> 32:22.348
I'm glad I talked Rachel
out of coming.

32:22.416 --> 32:24.617
She couldn't take this.

32:24.685 --> 32:26.452
I can't take it.

32:26.520 --> 32:29.422
Ames, look,
one more time--

32:29.490 --> 32:32.642
explain to me where Chance
and his team are going to be.

32:34.094 --> 32:35.261
Oh, ho ho ho ho.

32:35.329 --> 32:37.530
Never felt more ridiculous
in my life.

32:37.598 --> 32:39.832
<i>Where are you, Guerrero?</i>

32:39.900 --> 32:41.601
Is this somebody's idea
of a joke?

32:41.652 --> 32:43.620
A janitor again?

32:43.704 --> 32:46.939
What are you complaining about?
You see what I'm wearing?

32:46.991 --> 32:48.791
I thought you liked
Christmas.

32:48.876 --> 32:51.844
<i>Now, smile, will ya?</i>
<i>You're scaring the kids.</i>

32:51.912 --> 32:54.781
Okay, Ames, we're ready.
Start bringing Joel down.

32:54.848 --> 32:58.785
Okay, Joel,
it's time.

32:58.852 --> 33:01.254
This is our camera
and mic.

33:06.460 --> 33:07.694
<i>You're gonna do</i>
<i>great, son.</i>

33:07.761 --> 33:09.796
And remember...

33:09.863 --> 33:11.731
You're an Applebaum.

33:19.707 --> 33:26.879
♪ ♪

33:26.947 --> 33:28.981
<i>All right, he's heading</i>
<i>to the food court.</i>

33:29.033 --> 33:30.199
Got him.

33:41.879 --> 33:44.764
<i>There he is, Joel.</i>
<i>Make the drop.</i>

33:48.936 --> 33:49.969
<i>Joel, is that you?</i>

33:50.037 --> 33:52.171
Oh, my God,
you have got--

33:52.239 --> 33:53.906
oh, God, th--
that's Jamie!

33:53.974 --> 33:55.008
Who the hell's she?

33:55.075 --> 33:56.976
The entire school
is talking about it.

33:57.044 --> 33:58.844
We might have
a problem here, Chance.

33:58.896 --> 34:00.446
Jamie, I'll tell you
about it later,

34:00.514 --> 34:01.481
but right now
I have to go, okay?

34:01.548 --> 34:03.883
Come on, kid.
Lose her.

34:03.951 --> 34:06.152
Bring me the laptop...
And the boy.

34:06.220 --> 34:08.054
All right, people,
let's get ready to move.

34:08.121 --> 34:10.523
<i>Jamie, I really</i>
<i>have to go now, okay?</i>

34:10.591 --> 34:12.190
Look, just go now, okay?

34:12.259 --> 34:14.043
What the heck are you talking about?
It's time to go, Joel.

34:14.128 --> 34:15.460
<i>Chance, he's got Joel.</i>

34:15.529 --> 34:16.896
Let's go. Now.
<i>Excuse you!</i>

34:16.964 --> 34:18.715
We are trying to have
a private conversation here.

34:18.799 --> 34:21.000
I'm sorry, Jamie. I'm sorry.
I'll see you later, okay?
<i>Really?</i>

34:21.068 --> 34:22.435
<i>Where are we going?</i>

34:22.503 --> 34:24.804
They're not letting him go.
They're taking him.

34:27.408 --> 34:29.425
Here's the laptop.
I mean, you can just--

34:29.510 --> 34:31.543
look,
where are we going? I--

34:31.594 --> 34:35.447
<i>you--you just said</i>
<i>you needed the laptop.</i>

34:35.516 --> 34:36.616
You're being followed.

34:36.684 --> 34:39.185
<i>Stop them!</i>

34:49.530 --> 34:52.764
♪ I see trees of green ♪

34:52.833 --> 34:55.034
♪ red roses too ♪

34:55.101 --> 34:58.538
♪ I see them Bloom ♪

34:58.605 --> 35:00.573
♪ for me and you ♪

35:00.624 --> 35:04.711
♪ and I say to myself ♪

35:04.778 --> 35:10.350
♪ what a wonderful world ♪

35:11.785 --> 35:14.387
You okay?
Yeah, yeah, I think--yeah.

35:14.455 --> 35:15.755
Where's the bag?

35:15.823 --> 35:18.191
I don't--I don't know.

35:18.258 --> 35:20.643
♪ Bright sunny days ♪

35:20.728 --> 35:23.062
♪ dark sacred nights ♪

35:23.130 --> 35:27.233
♪ and I think to myself ♪

35:27.301 --> 35:29.285
♪ what a wonderful world ♪

35:33.307 --> 35:35.908
<i>That jackass</i>
<i>is ruining Christmas!</i>

35:35.976 --> 35:38.711
<i>Look out, look out!</i>

35:44.918 --> 35:48.788
♪ And I say to myself ♪

35:52.192 --> 35:55.995
♪ what a wonderful world ♪

35:56.063 --> 35:58.931
The mall at Christmas--
what a zoo.

36:09.372 --> 36:12.207
Fire in the hole.

36:12.275 --> 36:13.942
Oh!

36:14.010 --> 36:16.245
You're not the only
ones who live on the edge.

36:16.306 --> 36:17.740
Can't thank you enough.

36:17.808 --> 36:19.108
I talked to Hoxton-Moss.

36:19.176 --> 36:20.543
They said Meachem
was acting alone,

36:20.611 --> 36:22.912
and they're gonna cooperate
with the FDA, so I keep my job.

36:22.979 --> 36:24.731
That's good.
Glad we could be of help.

36:24.763 --> 36:26.181
Winston,
I'm gonna miss you.

36:26.265 --> 36:27.298
Aw...

36:27.349 --> 36:29.901
It was nice having
someone to talk to.

36:29.969 --> 36:31.903
Well, I hope it's gonna be
nicer to talk to me.

36:31.971 --> 36:33.605
I know I haven't been
very easy to live with,

36:33.672 --> 36:35.740
but that's gonna change,
I promise.

36:35.808 --> 36:37.175
Did you believe
any of that?

36:37.243 --> 36:38.510
Almost.

36:38.577 --> 36:39.861
Not so much.

36:39.945 --> 36:41.546
Well, it's not like
you're not gonna see me

36:41.614 --> 36:42.814
ever again, right?

36:42.882 --> 36:43.982
Thursday at 4:00?

36:44.049 --> 36:45.550
What's Thursday at 4:00?

36:45.618 --> 36:47.318
Book club.

36:47.386 --> 36:51.089
And that's a lovely tree
you have there, by the way.

36:51.156 --> 36:52.574
Thank you, Winston.

36:56.729 --> 36:57.712
Hey.

36:57.796 --> 37:00.048
Oh, uh, Jamie, hi.

37:00.132 --> 37:02.066
Um, how are you?

37:02.134 --> 37:04.269
I...

37:04.336 --> 37:06.070
<i>Sorry about the mix-up</i>
<i>at the mall.</i>

37:06.138 --> 37:07.572
I really didn't know
what I was thinking. Sorry.

37:07.640 --> 37:09.073
Are you kidding me?

37:09.141 --> 37:11.776
That was the coolest thing
I've ever seen!

37:11.844 --> 37:15.446
<i>You were like</i>
<i>a-a real-life action hero.</i>

37:15.514 --> 37:17.515
Uh, thanks.

37:21.253 --> 37:23.571
Um, well, great.
I guess, uh--

37:23.656 --> 37:25.523
I guess I'll see you
tomorrow.

37:26.792 --> 37:27.792
Joel!

37:32.464 --> 37:34.065
Jamie. Jamie, wait.

37:34.133 --> 37:35.233
I, um...

37:35.301 --> 37:38.036
That's, uh...

37:38.103 --> 37:40.371
Yeah, it's mistletoe.

37:46.378 --> 37:48.146
Oh. Hold on.

37:49.648 --> 37:52.917
Just give him a second.
He can handle it.

37:52.985 --> 37:55.119
He's an Applebaum.

38:02.227 --> 38:03.628
I'll see you tomorrow.

38:23.148 --> 38:24.082
Hey, dudes.

38:24.149 --> 38:26.417
What's up with this?

38:26.485 --> 38:28.620
Winston,
you shouldn't have.

38:28.687 --> 38:30.488
But I did.

38:30.556 --> 38:32.924
Merry Christmas, pal.

38:32.992 --> 38:34.525
Ho ho ho!

38:34.593 --> 38:36.344
Anybody want a scotch?

38:36.428 --> 38:38.329
Stole the bottle
from Meachem's office.

38:38.397 --> 38:40.064
Yeah.
I'll take a double.

38:51.010 --> 38:53.711
You know, I always wondered
what it would be like,

38:53.779 --> 38:56.047
you know,
to grow up in the burbs

38:56.115 --> 38:57.548
with a normal family.

38:57.616 --> 39:00.518
All I know is I'd rather
be tortured by a...

39:00.586 --> 39:01.853
Well, by me

39:01.920 --> 39:03.788
than ever have to go
back there again.

39:03.856 --> 39:05.156
Suburbs blow.

39:05.224 --> 39:06.958
All right,
that's it for me.

39:07.009 --> 39:08.292
I got to go.

39:08.360 --> 39:10.695
Yeah.
Yeah, me too.

39:10.763 --> 39:12.296
I'm exhausted.

39:12.364 --> 39:13.865
See you guys.

39:13.932 --> 39:15.700
Come on.
I'll give you a lift.

39:15.768 --> 39:17.702
I got a meeting
with the plumber.

39:17.770 --> 39:18.836
The plumber?

39:18.904 --> 39:20.338
Yeah, I don't want
to miss him.

39:20.406 --> 39:22.240
It's past midnight.

39:22.307 --> 39:24.976
It's not a plumber--
the plumber.

39:25.044 --> 39:27.945
Just--forget about it, dude.
You don't want to know.

39:42.561 --> 39:43.728
Oh, jeez!

39:43.796 --> 39:46.097
Yeah, I was just checking
the water.

39:49.201 --> 39:50.401
Ilsa.

39:50.469 --> 39:53.004
I thought you were gone
through new year's.

39:53.072 --> 39:54.238
You were right.

39:54.306 --> 39:56.207
About what?

39:57.844 --> 39:59.540
I went away
to throw myself into work,

39:59.640 --> 40:01.341
because I thought
it might help me forget

40:00.446 --> 40:03.748
about Marshall
being gone.

40:05.852 --> 40:06.848
But it didn't.

40:07.886 --> 40:10.254
Well, some things
you can't run away from,

40:10.322 --> 40:12.957
no matter how far
you go.

40:13.025 --> 40:15.026
Are you drinking alone
during the holidays?

40:15.077 --> 40:16.594
Not anymore.

40:20.332 --> 40:21.799
Even before
Marshall's death,

40:21.867 --> 40:24.435
this wasn't
my favorite time of year.

40:24.503 --> 40:26.003
Why not?

40:26.071 --> 40:27.839
Oh, I don't know.

40:27.906 --> 40:32.677
It always seemed a time
saved for normal families.

40:33.946 --> 40:36.280
That wasn't you?

40:36.348 --> 40:39.117
No, it wasn't.

40:40.652 --> 40:41.769
Well...

40:44.456 --> 40:46.224
Well, here's
to abnormal families.

40:52.164 --> 40:54.365
Say...

40:54.433 --> 40:56.167
Ilsa...

40:56.235 --> 40:57.835
Seeing that, you know,

40:57.903 --> 41:01.172
the holidays aren't really
all they're cracked up to be,

41:01.240 --> 41:04.308
what do you say we, uh,
get rid of that tree?

41:04.376 --> 41:06.944
It's more of a Winston thing.
I'm the only one who lives here.

41:07.012 --> 41:08.646
You're the boss.
That's true.

41:10.115 --> 41:12.817
But I quite like
what it represents--

41:12.885 --> 41:16.087
something to aspire to.

41:19.191 --> 41:20.992
The tree stays.

41:25.063 --> 41:26.798
Happy Christmas,
Mr. Chance.

41:26.865 --> 41:29.167
Merry Christmas,
Mrs. Pucci.

41:35.007 --> 41:43.030
♪ ♪

41:51.190 --> 41:52.723
♪ ♪

